<P class=3DMsoNormal style=3D"TEXT-ALIGN: center" =
align=3Dcenter><B><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt">FullText.exe for Full Text =
Analysis</SPAN></B></P>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt">FullText.exe is =
freely=20
available for academic usage. The program generates a word-occurrence =
matrix, a=20
co-occurrence matrix, and a normalized co-occurrence matrix from a set =
of text=20
files and a word list. The output files can be read into standard =
software (like=20
SPSS, Ucinet/Pajek, etc.) for the statistical analysis and the =
visualization. A=20
version adapted for the Korean character set is available at <A=20
href=3D"http://www.leydesdorff.net/krkwic">http://www.leydesdorff.net/krk=
wic</A> .=20
A similar program using lines (e.g., titles) instead of long texts can =
be=20
retrieved at <A=20
href=3D"http://www.leydesdorff.net/software/ti/index.htm">http://www.leyd=
esdorff.net/software/ti/index.htm</A>=20
.</SPAN></P>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt">input =
files</SPAN></I></P>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt">The program prompts =
for two=20
informations, notably, (a) the name of the file &lt;words.txt&gt; that =
contains=20
the words (as variables) to be analyzed in ASCII format and (b) the =
number of=20
files that contain the text elements as cases. The text elements are to =
be=20
numbered sequentially like Text1.txt, Text2.txt, etc. The number of =
texts is=20
unlimited; the size of the texts is also unlimited. The number of words =
is=20
limited to 1024, but keep in mind that many programs (e.g., Excel) will =
not=20
allow you to handle more than 256 variables in the follow-up. The words =
have to=20
be on separate lines which are ended with a hard character return and =
line feed.=20
(Save in Word as plain text with CR/LF or use a DOS utility for saving =
the file.=20
Make sure that lines are no longer than 100 characters each.)</SPAN></P>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<P class=3DMsoNormal style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 0.25in; TEXT-INDENT: =
-0.25in">=95<SPAN=20
style=3D"font-size-adjust: none; font-stretch: normal"><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 7pt">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; =
</SPAN></SPAN><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt">If the texts are less than 999 characters =
(e.g.,=20
titles), one can use <A=20
href=3D"http://www.leydesdorff.net/software/ti/index.htm">ti.exe=20
</A>instead.Ti.exe can handle an unlimited number of lines to a size of =
999=20
characters each.</SPAN></P>
<P class=3DMsoNormal style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 0.25in; TEXT-INDENT: =
-0.25in">=95<SPAN=20
style=3D"font-size-adjust: none; font-stretch: normal"><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 7pt">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; =
</SPAN></SPAN><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt">One can build a word frequency list with a =
concordance=20
program. For example, <A=20
href=3D"http://www.niederlandistik.fu-berlin.de/textstat/software-en.html=
">TextSTAT-2</A>=20
is freeware and online.</SPAN></P>
<P class=3DMsoNormal style=3D"MARGIN-LEFT: 0.25in; TEXT-INDENT: =
-0.25in">=95<SPAN=20
style=3D"font-size-adjust: none; font-stretch: normal"><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 7pt">&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp; =
</SPAN></SPAN><SPAN=20
style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt"><A=20
href=3D"http://www.leydesdorff.net/software/ti/stopword.exe">Stopword.exe=
</A> is=20
available for correction of a list with stopwords. Both list=97the lists =
of words=20
and stopwords=97have to be available in the same folder. The program =
does just=20
check the words in their current form (that is, without corrections for =
plural=20
or for uppercase/lowercase forms).</SPAN></P>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: =
12pt">&nbsp;&nbsp;</SPAN></P>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt">program =
file</SPAN></I></P>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt">The program is =
based on=20
DOS-legacy software from the 1980s (Leydesdorff, 1995). It runs in a =
MS-Dos=20
Command Box under Windows. The programs and the input files have to be =
contained=20
in the same directory. The output files are written into this directory =
as well.=20
Please, note that existing files from a previous run are overwritten by =
the=20
program. Save output elsewhere if you wish to continue with the=20
materials.</SPAN></P>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><I><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt">output =
files</SPAN></I></P>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt">The program =
produces three=20
output files in dBase IV format. These files can be read into Excel =
and/or SPSS=20
for further processing. Two files with the extension =93.dat=94 are in =
DL-format=20
(ASCII) and can be read into Pajek for the visualization (freely =
available at <A=20
href=3D"http://vlado.fmf.uni-lj.si/pub/networks/pajek/">http://vlado.fmf.=
uni-lj.si/pub/networks/pajek/</A>=20
).</SPAN></P>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt">a. <I>coocc.dbf =
</I>contains a=20
co-occurrence matrix of the words from this same data. This matrix is=20
symmetrical and it contains the words both as variables and as labels in =
the=20
first field. The main diagonal is set to zero. The number of =
co-occurrences is=20
equal to the multiplication of occurrences in each of the texts. (The =
procedure=20
is similar to using the file matrix.dbf as input to the routine =
=93affiliations=94=20
in UCINet, but the main diagonal is here set to zero in this matrix.) =
The file=20
<I>coocc.dat </I>contains this information in the DL-format.</SPAN></P>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt">b. <I>cosine.dbf =
</I>contains a=20
normalized co-occurrence matrix of the words from the same data. =
Normalization=20
is based on the cosine between the variables conceptualized as vectors =
(Salton=20
&amp; McGill, 1983). (The procedure is similar to using the file =
matrix.dbf as=20
input to the corresponding routing in SPSS.) The file <I>cosine.dat</I> =
contains=20
this information in the Pajek-format. The size of the nodes is equal to =
the=20
logarithm of the occurrences of the respective word; this feature can be =
turned=20
on in Pajek.</SPAN></P>
<P class=3DMsoNormal>&nbsp;</P>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt">c. <I>matrix.dbf =
</I>contains=20
an occurrence matrix of the words in the texts. This matrix is =
asymmetrical: it=20
contains the word numbers as the variables in the sequence order and the =
texts=20
as the cases. In other words, each row represents a text in the =
sequential order=20
of the text numbering, and each column represents a word in the =
sequential order=20
of the word list (v1, v2, etc.). (It is advisable to sort the word list=20
alphabetically before the analysis.) </SPAN></P>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt">An additional file=20
<I>labels.sps </I>is an SPSS syntax file and can be used for labeling =
the=20
variables with the words within SPSS. The words are counted as =
frequencies. (The=20
plural =93s=94 is removed before processing.) This file can be imported =
into SPSS=20
for further analysis.&nbsp;</SPAN></P>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt"></SPAN>&nbsp;</P>
<P class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt">d. <I>words.dbf</I> =
contains=20
for all words the following three summations: </SPAN></P>
<OL style=3D"MARGIN-TOP: 0in" type=3D1>
  <LI class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt">A variable named =
=93Chi_Sq=94=20
  which provides Chi-square contributions for each of the variables; =
these are=20
  defined for <I>word<SUB>i</SUB></I> as &#931;<SUB>i =
</SUB>&#967;<SUP>2</SUP> =3D=20
  (Observed<SUB>ij</SUB> =96 Expected<SUB>ij</SUB>)<SUP>2</SUP> /=20
  Expected<SUB>in</SUB>. In other words, the sum of the contributions =
over the=20
  column for the variable in each row (Mogoutov <I>et al</I>., 2008); =
</SPAN>
  <LI class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt">A variable named =
=93ObsExp=94=20
  which provides the sum of |Observed =96 Expected| for the word as a =
variable=20
  summed over the column;</SPAN>=20
  <LI class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt">A variable named =
=93TfIdf=94=20
  which use Salton &amp; McGill=92s (1983: 63)=20
  TermFrequency-InverseDocumentFrequency measure (but without Salton=92s =

  additional + 1; Magerman <I>et al</I>., 2007) defined as follows:=20
  WEIGHT<SUB>ik</SUB> =3D FREQ<SUB>ik</SUB> * [log<SUB>2</SUB> (n) =96=20
  log<SUB>2</SUB> (DOCFREQ<SUB>k</SUB>)]. This function assigns a high =
degree of=20
  importance to terms occurring in only a few documents in the=20
  collection;</SPAN>=20
  <LI class=3DMsoNormal><SPAN style=3D"FONT-SIZE: 12pt">The word =
frequency within=20
  the set. </SPAN></LI></OL>
